<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="typescript-strict-mode">
  <metadata>
    <tier>free</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>javascript-developer</domain>
    <summary>Strict-mode TypeScript with additional safety checks, null safety patterns, type narrowing, branded types, and const assertions for catching bugs at compile time.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>typescript</tag>
      <tag>strict-mode</tag>
      <tag>configuration</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>TypeScript Strict Mode</title>
    <summary>Full strict-mode configuration with additional safety checks, null safety patterns, type narrowing, branded types, and const assertions for catching whole classes of bugs at compile time.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>TypeScript's default settings permit implicit any, unchecked array access, and nullable function returns — all common sources of runtime errors. Enabling strict mode shifts those errors to compile time. noUncheckedIndexedAccess alone prevents 80%+ of out-of-bounds access bugs; exactOptionalPropertyTypes enforces the semantic difference between "missing" and "explicitly undefined".</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>All new TypeScript projects from day one</item>
        <item>JavaScript-to-TypeScript migration (enable flags incrementally)</item>
        <item>Library development where consumers depend on correct types</item>
        <item>Production applications requiring high reliability</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Auto-generated code (e.g., protobuf output) — add // @ts-nocheck per file instead</item>
        <item>Legacy codebases where enabling strict causes thousands of errors before a remediation plan exists — enable flags one at a time</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="TypeScript Strict Mode Configuration">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always set "strict": true and additionally enable noUncheckedIndexedAccess, exactOptionalPropertyTypes, noImplicitReturns, and noFallthroughCasesInSwitch.</statement>
        <rationale>"strict" covers 7 flags but leaves array access and optional/undefined semantics unchecked; the four additional flags close those gaps.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="json"><![CDATA[{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noUncheckedIndexedAccess": true,
    "exactOptionalPropertyTypes": true,
    "noImplicitReturns": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true,
    "noPropertyAccessFromIndexSignature": true,
    "target": "ES2022",
    "module": "ESNext",
    "moduleResolution": "bundler",
    "verbatimModuleSyntax": true,
    "isolatedModules": true,
    "skipLibCheck": true
  }
}]]></code>
      </example>
      <templates>
        <template path="templates/tsconfig.strict.json" purpose="Production-ready tsconfig with all strict flags"/>
      </templates>
    </section>
    <section name="noImplicitAny">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use unknown instead of any for values of unverified external origin; narrow before using.</statement>
        <rationale>unknown forces explicit type checking before access; any silently permits all operations including property access on undefined.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[function handleInput(input: unknown): void {
  if (typeof input === 'string') {
    console.log(input.toUpperCase()); // narrowed to string
  }
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="strictNullChecks">
      <rule>
        <statement>Return T | undefined from functions that can produce no result; throw with a message when the caller guarantees the value exists.</statement>
        <rationale>Returning T without null handling silently crashes at runtime; T | undefined forces the caller to handle the absent case.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[function getUser(id: string): User | undefined {
  return users.find(u => u.id === id);
}

function getRequiredUser(id: string): User {
  const user = users.find(u => u.id === id);
  if (!user) throw new Error(`User ${id} not found`);
  return user;
}

const userName = user?.name ?? 'Anonymous';]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="noUncheckedIndexedAccess">
      <rule>
        <statement>When accessing array elements by index, handle the T | undefined case before using the value.</statement>
        <rationale>Without this flag, arr[5] on a string[] has type string even though it may be undefined; the flag adds | undefined to make the risk explicit.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[function getFirst<T>(items: T[]): T | undefined {
  return items[0]; // correctly typed as T | undefined
}

function getFirstRequired<T>(items: T[]): T {
  const first = items[0];
  if (first === undefined) throw new Error('Array is empty');
  return first;
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="exactOptionalPropertyTypes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Omit optional properties rather than setting them to undefined; add | undefined to the type annotation when explicit undefined must be assignable.</statement>
        <rationale>exactOptionalPropertyTypes distinguishes "property absent" from "property present with value undefined" — a meaningful semantic difference for serialization and Object.keys enumeration.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[interface Config { timeout?: number }
const c1: Config = {};              // OK — omitted
// const c2: Config = { timeout: undefined }; // Error with exactOptionalPropertyTypes

interface ConfigExplicit { timeout?: number | undefined }
const c3: ConfigExplicit = { timeout: undefined }; // OK]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Type Guards and Discriminated Unions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Model sum types as discriminated unions with a literal discriminant field; use that field to narrow instead of type assertions.</statement>
        <rationale>Discriminated unions give exhaustiveness checking; type assertions bypass the type system and hide errors.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[type Result<T> =
  | { success: true; data: T }
  | { success: false; error: Error };

function handleResult<T>(result: Result<T>): T {
  if (result.success) {
    return result.data; // narrowed
  }
  throw result.error;  // narrowed
}

function isString(value: unknown): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="in and instanceof Narrowing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use the in operator to narrow between types that share a union but differ by property presence; use instanceof for class hierarchies.</statement>
        <rationale>These are the safe built-in narrowing forms — no risk of false narrowing that a manual cast would allow.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[interface Dog { bark(): void }
interface Cat { meow(): void }
function speak(animal: Dog | Cat): void {
  if ('bark' in animal) {
    animal.bark();
  } else {
    animal.meow();
  }
}

function formatDate(input: Date | string): string {
  if (input instanceof Date) {
    return input.toISOString();
  }
  return new Date(input).toISOString();
}]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Narrowing Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using the non-null assertion chain: user!.name!.first!</description>
        <reason>Every ! silently produces a TypeError at runtime if the value is actually null; use optional chaining and nullish coalescing instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Casting unknown external data with "as User".</description>
        <reason>Type assertions are unchecked — invalid shapes pass at compile time but crash at runtime. Validate with a type guard or Zod instead.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Branded Types">
      <rule>
        <statement>Brand primitive ID types to prevent accidental swap between semantically distinct IDs of the same underlying type.</statement>
        <rationale>UserId and OrderId are both strings — without branding, passing one where the other is expected compiles silently and fails at the data layer.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[type UserId = string & { readonly __brand: 'UserId' };
type OrderId = string & { readonly __brand: 'OrderId' };

function createUserId(id: string): UserId { return id as UserId; }
function createOrderId(id: string): OrderId { return id as OrderId; }

function getUser(id: UserId): User { /* ... */ return {} as User; }

const uid = createUserId('u-1');
const oid = createOrderId('o-1');
getUser(uid); // OK
// getUser(oid); // Error: OrderId not assignable to UserId]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Const Assertions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use "as const" on configuration objects and action-type maps to narrow to literal types and derive union types from values.</statement>
        <rationale>Without as const, string properties widen to string; with it they narrow to their literal values, enabling exhaustive discriminated unions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[const ACTIONS = {
  INCREMENT: 'INCREMENT',
  DECREMENT: 'DECREMENT',
} as const;

type ActionType = typeof ACTIONS[keyof typeof ACTIONS];
// Type: 'INCREMENT' | 'DECREMENT']]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Template Literal Type Contracts">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use template literal types to enforce URL prefix and HTTP method contracts at the type level.</statement>
        <rationale>Functions accepting arbitrary strings admit typos; template literal types constrain the shape without runtime checks.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[type HttpMethod = 'GET' | 'POST' | 'PUT' | 'DELETE';
type Endpoint = `/api/${string}`;

function request(method: HttpMethod, url: Endpoint): Promise<Response> {
  return fetch(url, { method });
}

request('GET', '/api/users');   // OK
// request('GET', '/users');    // Error: doesn't match /api/*
// request('PATCH', '/api/x'); // Error: PATCH not in HttpMethod]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
  </content>
</methodology>
